{"summary":"Accept all four amendments. Three identify concrete correctness/idempotency problems in retry and repair paths, and the duplication refactor is justified because the legacy task-run merge logic is subtle and should not live in two separate implementations.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-4-54b5dd71","decision":"accept","rationale":"The issue is real. `MilestoneSnapshot.updated_at` is defined as the last snapshot update time, but replaying a completion currently reuses the persisted terminal timestamp from lineage rather than the current update time. That can make `updated_at` move backward relative to later snapshot writes or remain stale after a retry. A monotonic assignment is the safer behavior."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-65a16a24","decision":"accept","rationale":"The duplicated attempt-collapse logic is subtle and affects both snapshot reconciliation and per-bead lineage queries. Keeping two near-identical implementations invites silent behavioral drift the next time legacy-merge rules change. Extracting one shared helper is a sound maintainability and robustness improvement."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-0195eaea","decision":"accept","rationale":"The no-`run_id` selector only accepts a single unsuperseded open row, so a legacy `running`+terminal pair with no `run_id` cannot be replayed even when it represents exactly one historical attempt. That breaks backward-compatible repair for existing NDJSON data and conflicts with the service contract that repeated terminal completions should repair snapshot/journal state without duplication."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-013c9cb2","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a concrete idempotency bug. `record_bead_start` appends the lineage row before snapshot/journal writes and does not deduplicate retries for the same `(bead_id, project_id, run_id)`. If the first start partially fails, a retry can leave duplicate running rows, and `update_task_run` will later reject completion as ambiguous because it finds multiple exact `run_id` matches."}]}